- The SM103 workaround is deliberately narrow: it only changes automatic/default ViT backend selection on compute capability 10.3. Explicit operator choice remains possible via `--mm-encoder-attn-backend`.
- If the backend falls through to `TORCH_SDPA`, startup may be slower but should be acceptable for proving health and requestability. The purpose of this branch is to prove FlashInfer 0.6.12rc1 in the vLLM image, not to optimize the multimodal profiling path.

## Codebase Discoveries
- `vllm-tensorizer/Dockerfile` mounts downloaded vLLM source into `/workspace` in the `vllm-builder` stage, so a source patch can be applied before `/opt/build.sh` without vendoring the whole vLLM checkout.
- `get_vit_attn_backend` in vLLM chooses the first supported backend from `get_supported_vit_attn_backends` when no backend is explicitly configured. On CUDA-capable devices this means `FLASH_ATTN` is tried before `TRITON_ATTN`, `TORCH_SDPA`, and `FLASHINFER`.
- The vLLM branch used by this image builds `v0.21.0` as a dev version string based on commit `ad7125a431e176d4161099480a66f0169609a690`.
- The existing Dockerfile already has a final dependency-pinning block for Kimi K2.5/vLLM runtime compatibility, so adding the `pytest` and `quack-kernels` pins there follows the local pattern.

